  <section id="modes">
    <div class="cgw-container">
      <p class="cgw-section-label fade-in">Safe control</p>
      <h2 class="section-title fade-in">Choose the right mode before you prompt</h2>
      <p class="section-intro fade-in">Mode selection is the difference between asking Copilot for advice and letting it make changes. Teach this early.</p>
      <div class="mode-grid">
        <article class="mode-card fade-in">
          <h3>Allow editing</h3>
          <p>Use when you want Copilot to directly insert, rewrite, reorganize, or transform document content.</p>
          <ul class="mode-list">
            <li>Best for early drafts and active editing.</li>
            <li>Use for section creation, restructuring, and rewriting.</li>
            <li>Review every change before sharing externally.</li>
          </ul>
        </article>
        <article class="mode-card fade-in">
          <h3>Chat only</h3>
          <p>Use when you want Copilot to respond in the pane without changing the document.</p>
          <ul class="mode-list">
            <li>Best for critique, Q&A, summarization, and planning.</li>
            <li>Use for sensitive, near-final, or reviewed documents.</li>
            <li>Copy or apply only the changes you approve.</li>
          </ul>
        </article>
      </div>
      <div class="callout fade-in">
        <strong>Rule of thumb:</strong> Chat only first for important documents. Allow editing after you know exactly what change you want.
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section id="workflow">
    <div class="cgw-container">
      <p class="cgw-section-label fade-in">Workflow</p>
      <h2 class="section-title fade-in">A repeatable way to work with Copilot in Word</h2>
      <p class="section-intro fade-in">Use this sequence for most business documents. It keeps Copilot useful while preserving human control.</p>
      <div class="workflow">
        <ol class="timeline fade-in">
          <li class="timeline-item">
            <span class="timeline-num">1</span>
            <div class="timeline-content"><h4>Choose the task</h4><p>Draft, edit, summarize, critique, transform, or prepare a role-specific deliverable.</p></div>
          </li>
          <li class="timeline-item">
            <span class="timeline-num">2</span>
            <div class="timeline-content"><h4>Choose the mode</h4><p>Use Allow editing for changes, Chat only for analysis or advice.</p></div>
          </li>
          <li class="timeline-item">
            <span class="timeline-num">3</span>
            <div class="timeline-content"><h4>Ground the prompt</h4><p>Attach the right file, cloud source, work content, or approved agent.</p></div>
          </li>
          <li class="timeline-item">
            <span class="timeline-num">4</span>
            <div class="timeline-content"><h4>Ask for structure</h4><p>Start with an outline, table, checklist, or section plan before a long draft.</p></div>
          </li>
          <li class="timeline-item">
            <span class="timeline-num">5</span>
            <div class="timeline-content"><h4>Iterate</h4><p>Regenerate, shorten, clarify, change tone, add missing sections, or ask for alternatives.</p></div>
          </li>
          <li class="timeline-item">
            <span class="timeline-num">6</span>
            <div class="timeline-content"><h4>Verify and finalize</h4><p>Check facts, numbers, citations, policy language, legal meaning, and customer commitments.</p></div>
          </li>
        </ol>
        <div class="prompt-builder fade-in">
          <h3>Prompt builder: GCSE</h3>
          <div class="prompt-row">
            <div class="prompt-label">Goal</div>
            <p>What do you want Copilot to create, edit, summarize, or analyze?</p>
          </div>
          <div class="prompt-row">
            <div class="prompt-label">Context</div>
            <p>Who is the audience? What business situation should shape the answer?</p>
          </div>
          <div class="prompt-row">
            <div class="prompt-label">Source</div>
            <p>What document, file, selected text, or approved agent should Copilot use?</p>
          </div>
          <div class="prompt-row">
            <div class="prompt-label">Expect</div>
            <p>What format, tone, length, sections, and guardrails should the output follow?</p>
          </div>
          <div class="prompt-output" onclick="copyPrompt(this)">
            <p>Using the attached source document, draft a one-page executive briefing for senior business leaders. Include context, key findings, decision needed, risks, recommendation, and open questions. Use concise business language, preserve all numbers exactly, and flag any assumptions or missing evidence.</p>
            <span class="copy-hint">Click to copy</span>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section id="advanced">
    <div class="cgw-container">
      <p class="cgw-section-label fade-in">Advanced features</p>
      <h2 class="section-title fade-in">Use agents, files, voice, and models intentionally</h2>
      <p class="section-intro fade-in">These capabilities make Copilot more powerful, but they also require clearer user judgment and governance awareness.</p>
      <div class="accordion">
        <div class="accordion-item fade-in">
          <button class="accordion-header" onclick="toggleAccordion(this)" aria-expanded="false">
            <span>Grounding with files and work content</span><span class="accordion-icon">+</span>
          </button>
          <div class="accordion-body"><div class="accordion-body-inner">
            Add work content, upload files, or attach cloud files when Copilot needs specific source material. Tell Copilot which source is authoritative and what it should not invent.
            <ul>
              <li>Use selected files for drafts and summaries.</li>
              <li>Use the current document for document Q&A and review.</li>
              <li>Use source constraints: "Only use the attached file and flag missing evidence."</li>
            </ul>
          </div></div>
        </div>
        <div class="accordion-item fade-in">
          <button class="accordion-header" onclick="toggleAccordion(this)" aria-expanded="false">
            <span>Agents: Researcher, Analyst, Legal Agent, and domain assistants</span><span class="accordion-icon">+</span>
          </button>
          <div class="accordion-body"><div class="accordion-body-inner">
            Agents extend Copilot with specialized instructions, knowledge, and sometimes actions. Use them when the task needs more than basic rewriting.
            <ul>
              <li>Researcher: source-backed briefs, market scans, backgrounders.</li>
              <li>Analyst: data interpretation, drivers, risks, recommendations.</li>
              <li>Domain agents: legal, HR, IT, sales, or process-specific guidance.</li>
            </ul>
          </div></div>
        </div>
        <div class="accordion-item fade-in">
          <button class="accordion-header" onclick="toggleAccordion(this)" aria-expanded="false">
            <span>Model selection: Auto, GPT, Claude, and reasoning options</span><span class="accordion-icon">+</span>
          </button>
          <div class="accordion-body"><div class="accordion-body-inner">
            Use Auto for most tasks. Choose a specific model only when your tenant exposes options and you have a reason, such as long-form synthesis, complex reasoning, or a preferred writing style.
            <ul>
              <li>Auto is the best default for general business users.</li>
              <li>Advanced reasoning can help with tradeoffs and complex analysis.</li>
              <li>Availability varies by license, policy, and service capacity.</li>
            </ul>
          </div></div>
        </div>
        <div class="accordion-item fade-in">
          <button class="accordion-header" onclick="toggleAccordion(this)" aria-expanded="false">
            <span>Voice input vs Word Dictate</span><span class="accordion-icon">+</span>
          </button>
          <div class="accordion-body"><div class="accordion-body-inner">
            Word Dictate turns speech into document text. The microphone in the Copilot box sends a spoken instruction to Copilot.
            <ul>
              <li>Use Dictate to capture raw ideas.</li>
              <li>Use Copilot voice input to ask Copilot to perform a task.</li>
              <li>Verify names, numbers, acronyms, and sensitive details before submitting.</li>
            </ul>
          </div></div>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

